      <task workspace="6cm" xml:id="act-4-4-2-task-0">
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>\displaystyle \int_0^1 \left(x^3 - x - e^x + 2\right) \,dx</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <hint/>
        <answer>
          <p><m> \int_0^1 \left(x^3 - x - e^x + 2\right) \,dx = \frac{11}{4} - e</m>.
          </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
          <p>
            By standard antiderivative rules and the FTC,
            <md><mrow>\int_0^1 \left(x^3 - x - e^x + 2\right) \,dx =\mathstrut \amp  \left. \frac{1}{4} x^4 - \frac{1}{2}x^2 - e^x + 2x \right|_0^1</mrow><mrow>=\mathstrut \amp  \left(\frac{1}{4} (1)^4 - \frac{1}{2}(1)^2 - e^1 + 2(1) \right) -   \left(\frac{1}{4} (0)^4 - \frac{1}{2}(0)^2 - e^0 + 2(0) \right)</mrow><mrow>=\mathstrut \amp  \frac{1}{4} - \frac{1}{2} - e + 2 -  \left(0 - 0 - 1 + 0 \right)</mrow><mrow>=\mathstrut \amp  -\frac{1}{4} - e + 3</mrow><mrow>=\mathstrut \amp  \frac{11}{4} - e</mrow></md>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task workspace="6cm" xml:id="act-4-4-2-task-1">
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>\displaystyle \int_0^{\pi/3} (2\sin (t) - 4\cos(t) + \sec^2(t) - \pi) \, dt</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <hint/>
        <answer>
          <p><m> \int_0^{\pi/3} (2\sin (t) - 4\cos(t) + \sec^2(t) - \pi) \, dt = 1 - \sqrt{3} - \frac{\pi^2}{3}</m>.
          </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
          <p>
            Calculating the needed antiderivative and applying the FTC,
            <md><mrow>\int_0^{\pi/3} (2\sin (t) - 4\cos(t) + \sec^2(t) - \pi) \, dt =\mathstrut \amp  \left. \left(-2\cos(t) - 4\sin(t) + \tan(t) - \pi t \right) \right|_0^{\pi/3}</mrow><mrow>=\mathstrut \amp  \left(-2\cos(\pi/3) - 4\sin(\pi/3) + \tan(\pi/3) - \pi (\pi/3) \right) -</mrow><mrow>\ \amp   \left(-2\cos(0)) - 4\sin(0) + \tan(0) - \pi (0) \right)</mrow><mrow>=\mathstrut \amp  -2 \cdot \frac{1}{2} - 4 \cdot \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} + \sqrt{3} - \frac{\pi^2}{3} - (-2 - 0 + 0 - 0)</mrow><mrow>=\mathstrut \amp  1 - \sqrt{3} - \frac{\pi^2}{3}</mrow></md>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task workspace="6cm" xml:id="act-4-4-2-task-2">
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>\displaystyle \int_0^1 (\sqrt{x}-x^2) \, dx</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <hint/>
        <answer>
          <p><m> \int_0^1 (\sqrt{x} - x^2) \, dx = \frac{1}{3}</m>.
          </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
          <p>
            Noting that <m>\frac{d}{dx}[\frac{2}{3} x^{3/2}] = x^{1/2}</m>,
            we find that
            <md><mrow>\int_0^1 (\sqrt{x} - x^2) \, dx =\mathstrut \amp  \left. \frac{2}{3}x^{3/2} - \frac{1}{3}x^3 \right|_0^1</mrow><mrow>=\mathstrut \amp  \frac{2}{3} - \frac{1}{3} - (0 - 0 )</mrow><mrow>=\mathstrut \amp  \frac{1}{3}</mrow></md>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <hint>
        <p>
      For the table,
      you might start by constructing a list of all the basic functions whose derivative you know.
      For the three definite integrals,
      be sure to recall the sum and constant multiple rules,
      which work not only for differentiating,
      but also for antidifferentiating.
    </p>
